The Definicon Systems Librarian was developed by Computer Systems 
Design,  North Perth Australia, for the DSI-32 coprocessor board.  
All  references to Definicon Systems Librarian are references  to 
the Computer Systems Design version of the librarian.
.pa
                            Chapter 1

                        THE LIB LIBRARIAN


1.1  INTRODUCTION

LIB  is  an  object file librarian which enables  several  object 
files,  generated  by AS (the DSI-32 assembler),  to be  inserted 
into a  single object file.  This single object file may then  be 
used  as a library for  LN (the DSI-32 linker).  The  library  is 
easily accessed with the LIBRARY directive of LN.  LN will search 
the   library  to  resolve  any  unsatisfied  imports  and   will 
automatically  recursively search and attempt to satisfy any  new 
unsatisfied  imports due to including any of the library modules.

The features of the LIB librarian are:

     o    Complete  set  of  directives available for  easy  and 
          efficient management of libraries.
     o    Librarian can be driven interactively or by  a  command
          file.
     o    Modules can be inserted or deleted.
     o    Optional  Map  of  all modules in the  library  can  be           
          generated.
     o    Up to 500 separately compiled modules can be put into a
          single library.

1.2  INPUT AND OUTPUT FILES USED AND GENERATED BY LIB

LIB  manages   object modules produced by AS and generates a  new 
library file.   An optional map file may be generated by  issuing 
the LIST directive to the librarian.

Object  file  - Input.   The object code  and  associated  tables 
generated by AS are in this file.  The default filename extension 
for object files is .O32.

Indirect  file - Input.   The indirect (command) file contains  a 
list  of librarian directives used to drive the librarian without 
requiring  interactive input.   The directives supported  by  the 
indirect  file  are the same as those used in  interactive  mode, 
except  that embedded indirect commands are not  supported.   See 
section 1.6 for a discussion of interactive and indirect modes of 
input.
.pa
Library  file  - Output.   The  result  of  a  session  with  the 
librarian is a new or modified library file. The file may then be 
searched  by LN to satisfy unresolved imports.  The library  file 
has  an  added feature;  to LN it appears as a  concatenation  of 
object  files  and can be totally included in an executable  file 
via  the FILE= directive.   The default extension for  a  library 
file is .O32. 

Map  file  - Output.   If  the LIST directive  is  given  to  the 
librarian,  all  statistics  of  each module in  the  library  is 
displayed.  The listing may be re-directed to a file via the OUT= 
directive. 

Errors and Warnings - Output.  Errors detected by the librarian, 
whether operating in interactive or indirect (command file)  mode 
are  sent to the console immediately after the error occurs.   In 
indirect mode,  error messages are displayed after the  directive 
which  caused  the error  has been echoed to the  console.   Some 
directives  will  cause the librarian to exit  to  the  operating 
system  if  an error is detected,  whereas others will cause  the 
librarian to return to the interactive mode for further input.

1.3  LIB INVOCATION

The  Librarian may be invoked in an interactive mode  or  command 
line  mode.   Interactive mode allows the user to specify several 
directives,  one at a time to the librarian. As it processes each 
directive it immediately reports any errors.   Command line  mode 
allows  the user to list on the operating system command line all 
the necessary directives for linking.

Interactive  mode  is entered by simply typing  "LIB"  after  the 
system  prompt.   Command line mode in invoked by specifying  the 
librarian directives immediately after "LIB".  Both modes use the 
same directives and require the same format for each directive.

When  invoked in interactive mode,  the librarian displays a LIB> 
prompt  on  the screen and waits for the user to  start  entering 
directives.   The user then enters the directives,  one directive 
at  a time followed by a carriage return (<CR>),  until the  full 
set  of  directives necessary for linking  have  been  specified.    
If a directive is improperly specified,  or a directive confilcts 
with a previouly entered directive, the librarian will display an 
error  message immediately after the directive has been  entered. 
When all directives have been entered,  a blank line (i.e. a line 
containing  only  a  <CR>) instructs the librarian  to  link  the 
modules  specified under the constraints of the  directives.   If 
all necessary directives have not been specified,  the  librarian 
will display an error message reporting that fact.   Depending on 
the severity of the error,  the librarian will return to the LIB> 
prompt, or return to the operating system.
As  an example of interactive mode,  the following is  a  session 
using  LIB  to link three modules named a.o32,  b.o32  and  c.o32 
producing a new library named d.o32.

     C>LIB
     DSI-32 Librarian V1.00, Definicon Systems Inc.
     LIB> FILE=D/NEW
     LIB> ADD=A,B,C
     LIB>
     C>

Whether  invoked in command line mode or interactive  mode,  each 
directive  specified  on  the  command or  prompt  line  must  be 
separated by blanks.   Directives themselves,  however,  must not 
contain  blanks.   For example,  to link the same modules in  the 
above example in command line mode,  the following MS-DOS command 
line is used:

     C>LIB FILE=D/NEW ADD=A,B,C
     DSI-32 Librarian V1.00, Definicon Systems Inc.
     C>

Note  that  the single directive ADD,  though it refers to  three 
file names,  does not contain imbedded blanks, whereas a blank is 
necessary  to separate the FILE directive from the ADD directive.  
This  requirement  is the same in both indirect  and  interactive 
modes.

1.4  RESOLVING EXTERNAL REFERENCES

LIB  resolves  external  references  by  searching  each   module 
specified  by the FILE directive.  If LIB detects that more  than 
one  module is exporting the same symbol name a  warning  message 
will  be displayed when the LIST directive is invoked. 
.pa
1.5  DIRECTIVES

Directives  provide the librarian with the information  necessary 
to successfully create or manage a library file.  The format of a 
directive is:

     dir=spec

where dir is one of LIB's directive keywords and spec is variable 
information  that is significant in the context of the directive.  
Note  that  no  spaces  are allowed  between  any  parts  of  the 
directive.

Directives  fall into two categories depending on how many  times 
they may appear in a link session.  Cummulative directives may be 
specified  more  than once during a link  session,  whereas  non-
cummulative  directives  may be specified a maximum of  one  time 
during any link session.   Specifying a non-cummulative directive 
more than once will cause LIB to generate an error and/or  return 
to the operating system.  The cummulative directives are:

     ADD, LIST, REP, DEL, SHOW, EXT

All  other directives fall into the non-cummulative category  and 
therefore may be specified only once.

LIB  identifies  a  directive by the first n  characters  of  the 
keyword  which  uniquely  distinguish it from  other  directives.  
This  allows  for  abbreviated  specification  of  the  directive 
keyword.  For example,  EXI uniquely identifies the EXIT  keyword 
and  distinguishes it from the EXT directive. 
.pa
1.5.1  INPUT DIRECTIVES

The  INPUT  directives  specify the names of the  work  file  and 
object  files  that  the  librarian  is  to  operate  upon.   The 
directives are:

     o    FILE
     o    ADD
     o    REP
     o    DEL
     o    EXT
     o    IND

1.5.1.1   The FILE directive

Format:   FILE=<filename>[/<new>]...

description:

          FILE           is the directive keyword

          filename       is  the name of the work  file generated 
                         by  LIB.  The default filename extension 
                         is .O32.

The FILE directive specifies the name of the work file that is to 
be  created (if the <new> directive is issued),  or operated  on. 
This  directive  must  be issued at least once  in  each  library 
session.  Note,  invoking this directive is equivalent to exiting 
the librarian and then invoking it again,  ie. it resets the link 
session.

If LIB determines that a file is unusable (i.e.  not found,  file 
is empty, or not an object file), an error message is sent to the 
console.

Examples:

     1.   LIB> FILE=MYLIB
     2.   LIB> F=MYLIB/NEWO

In  example  1,  the library file,  MYLIB is assumed  to  already 
exist.  Note that no spaces exist between the filenames.

In  example 2,  "F" uniquely defines the FILE directive the  /NEW 
switch  informs  LIB to erase any old copy of MYLILB.O32  and  to 
create a new empty copy.
.pa
1.5.1.2   The ADD directive

Format:   ADD=<filename>[,<filename>...]

description:

          ADD            is the directive keyword

          filename       is  the name of an object  file  to  be
                         linked into the library work file. The 
                         The default extension is .O32.

The  ADD  directive specifies the object file(s) to  be  inserted 
into the current library work file. 

This directive is a cummulative directive (see section 1.5) which 
allows the user repeated invocation of the ADD specification.

If LN determines that a file is unusable (i.e. not found, file is 
empty,  not  an  object  file,  or the module is already  in  the 
library), an error message is sent to the console.

Examples:

     1.   LIB> ADD=LIB1,LIB2,LIB3.O32,LIB4
          LIB> ADD=LIB5,LIB0
     2.   LIB> AD=LIB0.O

In  example 1,  the librarian is given two ADD  directives.  Note 
that each ADD directive may contain more than one file (each file 
name must be separated by a comma).

In example 2,  the abbreviated form of the ADD directive is  used 
and  a non default extension is specified for LIB0  object  file. 
The  librarian assumes that object files have a .O32 extension by 
default, though it may be overridden with an explicitly specified 
filename.
.pa
1.5.1.3   The REP directives

Format:   REP=<filename>[,<filename>..]

description:

          REP            is the directive keyword

          filename       is  the  name of  the  object  file  to 
                         replace or insert if not already there.

The REP directive informs the librarian to attempt to replace the 
module  in  the  current work file with the  new  module  in  the 
specified file.  If the module does not already exist in the work 
file, then it is inserted. 

Example:

       LIB> REP=T1,T2

In  this  example the modules in the two files,  T1 and  T2  will 
replace the old versions that are currently in the work file.  If 
they are not already in the work file then they will be inserted.
.pa
1.5.1.4   The DEL directive

Format:   DEL=<modulename>[,<modulename>...]

description:

          DEL            is the directive keyword

          modulename     is  the name of a  module that is to be 
                         deleted from the library file.

The DEL directive specifies which module(s) is to be deleted from 
the  current library work file.  Note that this directive  causes 
irreversible deletion of the specified module(s).  Also note that 
each deleted module still occupies space in the object  file,  to 
return  this  free  space  it is necessary  to  invoke  the  PACK 
directive.

Examples:

       LIB> DEL=FILE1

In this example the module FILE1 will be deleted from the current 
work  file  (if it exists).  Note that the librarian is not  case 
sensitive when dealing with module names.
.pa
1.5.1.5   The EXT directive

Format:   EXT=<modulename>/FILE=<filename>

description:

          EXT            is the directive keyword

          modulename     is  the name of  a  module  contained to 
                         extract from the work file. 

          filename       is the  name of  the file  to  place the
                         extracted module into.

The  EXT  directive specifies which module to  extract  from  the 
current library work file and which file to copy the module to. 
This directive enables the user to specify a module that is to be 
extracted  from current work file and the name of the object file 
that it is to be copied to.

Note that the original work file is not altered in any way.

Example:

       LIB> EXT=T1/FILE=TEST

In  this example the module T1 will be extracted from the current 
library work file and placed in a file named TEST.O32 . 

Note  that  only  one module at a time may be  extracted  from  a 
library. Also the destination file is always overwritten, so that 
if  a  new  library file is to be created  each  module  must  be 
extracted  into  a separate file and then individually  added  to 
either an old or new library file.
.pa
1.5.1.6   The PACK directive

Format:   PACK

description:

          PACK           is the directive keyword


The  PACK directive will inform the librarian that the user wants 
to  attempt  to compress the library file after files  have  been 
replaced   or  deleted.   Since  this  directive  performs  major 
rewriting  of the current work file it may be advisable  to  copy 
the  work  file  to a temporary file in case of a power  fail  or 
other computer failure while the librarian is packing the file.

Example:

       LIB> PACK

In  this  example the librarian will attempt to pack the  current 
work file. 

Note.  The  librarian will issue an error if there is  no  active 
work  file.  The  error  is non-fatal and the  link  session  may 
continue  after  the  user specifies the work file  to  use,  see 
Section 1.5.1.1
.pa
1.5.2  INDIRECT DIRECTIVE

The  INDIRECT FILE directive specifies which  indirect  (command) 
files  are  to be used in controlling the library  session.   The 
directive is:

     o    INDIRECT

For  a full discussion on how to use the librarian with  indirect 
files, see section 1.6. The indirect files enable the user to put 
often  used  link directives into a single file.  This is  useful 
while  developing  a  libarary or for rebuilding a  library  when 
major  portions  are changed.  Typically the indirect  file  will 
contain  the FILE directive and all the required  ADD  directives 
for all the files that are to be inserted into the library.
.pa
1.5.2.1   The INDIRECT directive

Format:   INDIRECT=<filename>

description:

          INDIRECT       is the directive keyword

          filename       is the name of an ASCII file  containing 
                         LIB  directives.    The   default   file 
                         extension is .IND.

The INDIRECT directive specifies the name of a file to be used to 
direct the librarian.

When  the  INDIRECT directive is used,  the librarian  opens  the 
specified  file and begins interpreting the text in the file in a 
similar manner to keyboard input.  The syntax used for directives 
in indirect files is identical to that for interactive input.

As the librarian processes an INDIRECT directive,  it echoes  the 
directive  to  the  console preceeded with an at  (@)  sign.   If 
during the processing of the directive an error is detected,  the 
librarian sends an error message to the console immediately after 
the command.   In interactive mode,  the librarian returns to the 
LIB> prompt after the indirect file has been fully processed.  If 
the  librarian  is in non-interactive  mode,  after  it  finishes 
processing  the indirect file,  it processes the default file and 
proceeds  to link the modules and then returns to  the  operating 
system.

INDIRECT  directives  cannot be used  in  indirect  files.   Link 
directives (<CR>) are not processed in indirect files.

Examples:

     1.   LIB> IND=TEST

     2.   C>LIB IND=TEST

In example 1,  the INDIRECT directive is used to specify the file 
TEST.IND  as the indirect file.   This example is in  interactive 
mode.

In  example 2,  the INDIRECT directive is specified in the MS-DOS 
command line and causes the linker to process in  non-interactive 
mode.
.pa
1.5.3  OUTPUT DIRECTIVES

The   OUTPUT  directives  control  the  output  of  the   various 
statistical information about the library file.  These directives 
are:

     o    OUT
     o    LIST
     o    SHOW


1.5.3.1   The OUT directive

Format:   OUT[=<filename>]

description:

          OUT            is the directive keyword

          <filename>     is the name of the output file to which
                         the list data is to be output to.

The  OUT directive informs the librarian that all listing  output 
generated by the LIST directive is to go to a data file. 

If  no OUT directive is isssued then the librarian  will  display 
all text data to the console. 

Examples:

     1.   LIB> OUT
     2.   LIB> OUT=LISTFILE

In example 1,  the librarian is informed that all listing data is 
to be displayed on the console. 

In example 2, the librarian is informed to create a file with the 
name  LISTFILE.L32  and then to direct any output from  the  LIST 
directive to that file.
.pa
1.5.3.2   The LIST directive

Format:   LIST

description:

          LIST           is the directive keyword


The  LIST directive specifies that a map file is to be  generated 
and  displayed on the console.  The map file displays information 
on  each module in the work file.  The information  includes  the 
language  type of the module,  the number of imports and exports, 
all  the  imports and exports and whether the imports  have  been 
resolved and which module they have been resolved in.

Example:

     LIB> LIST

In  the  example,  a map file is generated and displayed  on  the 
console  unless an OUT=<filename> directive was issued,  in which 
case all output is directed to <filename>.
.pa
1.5.3.3   The SHOW directive

Format:   SHOW

description:

          SHOW           is the directive keyword


The  SHOW  directive  displays on the console  the  name  of  the 
current work file and the name of the current output file, if one 
has been specified with the OUT directive. 

Example:

     LIB> SHOW
     Work file: LIBA.O32
     Out file : --- none ---
     LIB>

In  the example,  the current work file is LIBA.O32 and no output 
file has been requested.
.pa
1.5.4  LIBRARIAN CONTROL DIRECTIVES

The  CONTROL  directives control the  execution  of  LIB.   These 
directives are:

     o    QUIT/EXIT
     o    link (<CR>)


1.5.4.1   The QUIT and EXIT directives

Format:   QUIT
          EXIT

description:

          QUIT, EXIT     are the directive keywords

The QUIT and EXIT function identically.   They terminate the link 
session  and return control to the MS-DOS operating system.  Note 
the QUIT and EXIT commands may only be issued when the  librarian 
prompt  is  displayed and the librarian is waiting  for  keyboard 
input.  To  terminate  linking when the librarian prompt  is  not 
displayed, the the Control C sequence must be entered.  No output 
files are generated when these directives are used.
.pa
1.5.4.2   The link (<CR>) directive

Format:   <CR>

description:

          <CR>           is a carriage return character

The  link directive is specified by entering a  <CR>  immediately 
after  the  LIB>  prompt.   This directive is only  available  in 
interactive mode.

After specifying all necessary directives for a successful  link, 
the link directive tells the librarian to execute the link  based 
on  the specifications of the previously entered directives.   If 
all directives have been specified correctly,  the librarian will 
finish  up all library maintenance,  close the work file and exit 
back to the operating system. 

Example:

     C>LIB
     DSI-32 Librarian V1.00, Definicon Systems Inc.
     LIB> FILE=TEST1/NEW
     LIB> ADD=TEST2,TEST3
     LIB> SHOW
     LIB> 

     C>
In  the example,  the library file  TEST1.O32 is created and  the 
object  files  TEST2.O32  and TEST3.O32 are added  to  the  empty 
library file.   Note that the last line of the linker  directives 
is a carriage return character.
.pa
1.6  USE OF INDIRECT FILES

Indirect  files give the user an easy method of  instructing  the 
librarian  what is to be performed in a link session,  by using a 
file  containing  a set of directives for  linking,  rather  than 
having  to  re-enter  the set of directives each  time  the  same 
sequence is to be performed. 

Indirect files can be specified in two ways.   First,  using  the 
command  line mode,  an indirect file can be specified by  typing 
"LIB  IND=filename" where filename is a file containing librarian 
directives.   This  instructs  the  librarian to  open  the  file 
filename  and  take instructions from  that  file.   The  default 
extension  on indirect files is .IND.   The second way to specify 
indirect  files  is  after invoking  interactive  mode,  use  the 
INDIRECT directive to specify an indirect file.  Execution of the 
librarian  will  then proceed with directives from  the  indirect 
file.

When  invoked in indirect mode,  the librarian takes   directives 
from the specified indirect file until it reaches the end of  the 
file.   When  a  directive is read from the file,  the  librarian 
processes the directive,  echoes the directive to the console and 
reports  any  errors to the console before going on to  the  next 
directive.   If an error occurs,  processing will always continue 
until the complete file has been read.  Depending on the severity 
of the error,  however,  the librarian will return control to the 
LIB> prompt or to operatingh system.

If, for example the file a.ind has the following directives,

     FILE=a.o32
     ADD=b.o32,c.o32

then  the  following  command  sequences  can  be  used  to  take 
advantage of them:

     C>LN IND=a.ind
          @ FILE=A.O32
          @ ADD=B.O32,C.O32
     C>

or

     C>LIB
     DSI-32 Librarian V1.00, Definicon Systems Inc.
     LIB> IND=a.ind
         @ FILE=A.O32
         @ ADD=B.O32,C.O32
     C>

